en told. Alex Drace-Francis surveys the arrival and spread of maize cultivation in Romanian lands from Ottoman times to the eve of the First World War, and also the image of mămăligă in art and popular culture. Drawing on a rich array of sources and with many new findings, Drace-Francis shows how the making of mămăligă has been shaped by global economic forces and overlapping imperial systems of war and trade.  The story of maize and mămăligă provides an accessible way to revisit many key questions of Romanian and broader regional history. More generally, the book links the history of production, consumption, and representation. Analyses of recipes, literary and popular depictions, and key vocabulary complete the work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aCooking (Corn)zRomaniaxHistory. 0aNational characteristcs. 0aPolentazRomaniaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  aFood & cuisine.  aMaize.  aRomania.  aagriculture.  anational identity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2022z978311078048240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789633865842?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633865842423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633865842/original  a978-3-11-078048-2  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK